    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that's a bit clearer thanks. so if the money is just sitting there with a third party, what happens if there's a dispute during the process? like if the inspection shows something was wrong and i want to hold back some of the money? does the escrow agent just decide who gets it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, disputes in the realm of real estate can indeed be as tricky as navigating a goblin's maze. If an inspection reveals issues with the property, you may have grounds to negotiate with the seller or even back out of the deal, depending on the terms of your contract. In such cases, the funds in the escrow account are typically frozen until the dispute is resolved. The escrow agent acts as a neutral party, holding the funds in abeyance and not making decisions about who gets the money. Instead, they follow the instructions of the parties involved, as outlined in the escrow agreement. If you and the seller cannot agree, you may need to involve your real estate attorney or mediator to help resolve the issue. The escrow agent will release the funds only when all conditions are met and both parties are satisfied, or when a legal decision has been made regarding the dispute.",
